
Stage 0 is build-system-owned input preparation.
It builds the module inputs consumed by the frontend.

It isn't semantic frontend compilation.
It shouldn't type-check executable code, fold ordinary module constants for language use or decide HIR shape.
It finds the files, config and builder surfaces that the frontend needs.

## Main path

`src/build_system/create_project_modules/`

Important owners:

- `src/build_system/project_config.rs` and `src/build_system/project_config/` own `config.bst` parsing, AST-backed value extraction and shape validation.
- `compilation.rs`, `project_roots.rs` and `frontend_orchestration.rs` own single-file/directory dispatch, root interpretation, prepared resolver setup and per-module frontend orchestration.
- `source_tree_index.rs`, `module_inventory.rs`, `reachable_file_discovery.rs`, `import_scanning.rs` and `source_loading.rs` own one-pass root discovery, import-graph traversal and source loading.
- `source_package_discovery.rs`, `root_validation.rs`, `collision_detection.rs`, `project_structure_diagnostics.rs` and `source_discovery_error.rs` own source-backed package root preflight, package-prefix collision checks, typed Stage 0 diagnostics and diagnostic/infrastructure error boundaries.

## What Stage 0 owns

Stage 0 owns:

- parsing `config.bst` and reachable core/builder source-backed package support files through the frontend up to AST
- extracting only authored known top-level `#` config-key constants from shared AST const facts
- enforcing each config key's registered value shape before core fields are applied or backend settings are stored
- allowing config imports only from Core or Builder packages
- rejecting project-local and relative config imports by design
- stopping config compilation at AST because config doesn't need HIR
- building one source-tree index after config establishes `entry_root`, `package_folders` and output folders
- selecting exactly one cosmetic non-config `#*.bst` root per module directory
- expanding each module to reachable `.bst` files and builder-supported source assets through imports
- preparing canonical source-backed package roots and their unique hash-root public-surface files before resolver construction
- recognising external package prefixes so virtual imports aren't treated as filesystem paths
- resolving source-kind candidates through the builder-provided registry
- resolving provider-backed external file imports before AST and storing typed package metadata in the external import resolution table
- rejecting sibling `.bst` file/folder import-name collisions and special-file imports before semantic compilation
- recording source file identities for later diagnostics and path rendering

Private inferred const facts are collected after dependency sorting and AST construction.
They don't participate in header dependency sorting and don't become importable declarations.

## Config boundary

`config.bst` is a special frontend client, not a normal module.

It can use compile-time constants, folded templates, core/builder support imports and typed diagnostics.
It can't produce HIR, runtime `start` code or language-visible exports.

This is why Stage 0 stops config compilation at AST.
The build system needs folded config values and typed errors, not backend-facing runtime code.

## Source discovery

Stage 0 indexes directory projects once, then reuses that immutable root table for module inventory and nearest-root lookup. Output folders and irrelevant hidden or generated trees are skipped by the index owner.

`ProjectPathResolver` consumes `PreparedSourcePackageRoots` plus the source-tree index. Resolver construction performs no filesystem discovery. This keeps path resolution a lookup layer and prevents hidden rescans per module.

Reachable-file discovery expands each selected module to imported `.bst` files and builder-supported source assets. It also recognises external package prefixes so virtual imports don't become filesystem lookups.

Plain Markdown `.md` and Beandown `.bd` files are builder-supported source assets.
They are discovered through the same extensionless source import candidate path as `.bst` files when the builder declares support.

## Parallel inventory work

Multi-entry directory builds may run module inventory discovery in parallel only after a serial provider-free classification proves that no reachable import needs an external import provider or unsupported external-extension diagnostic.

That classification also carries scanned Beanstalk source text forward so provider-free workers don't re-read the same files.
Provider-capable discovery remains serial because it mutates the external package registry, provider cache, resolution table and shared diagnostic string table.

Parallel provider-backed discovery needs deterministic provider deltas and ID remapping first.
Without that, IDs and diagnostics can drift by thread scheduling.

## Reusing loaded source

Reachable-file discovery reuses Beanstalk source text read during import scanning when assembling `InputFile` values.
Files not scanned for imports, such as plain Markdown and Beandown assets, are loaded through a threshold-gated missing-source path.

Small miss sets stay serial.
Larger miss sets use Rayon, then rejoin in deterministic inventory order before header preparation sees them.

## String-table boundary

For directory builds, Stage 0 owns the build-boundary string-table fork/merge lifecycle.
Module frontend jobs receive local string-table deltas.
The build system merges those deltas back into the shared build table after compilation has completed.

The module frontend owns its own internal per-file fork/merge lifecycle before dependency sorting.
Don't mix these two layers.

## What Stage 0 should not do

Stage 0 should not:

- perform semantic frontend compilation for normal modules
- create HIR
- run borrow validation
- infer language semantics from executable bodies
- treat provider-backed external files as source modules
- let config imports reach project-local or relative paths
- bypass typed diagnostics for project-structure mistakes

If Stage 0 starts needing semantic type facts from a normal module, something is probably crossing the build-system/frontend boundary.

